---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import { buildBreadcrumbList } from '../../lib/structured-data';

const siteUrl = Astro.site?.toString().replace(/\/$/, '') ?? 'https://zolotukhin.ai';
const breadcrumbItems = [
  { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { name: 'ZINC' },
];

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'SoftwareApplication',
      name: 'ZINC',
      description: 'LLM inference engine for AMD RDNA3/RDNA4 consumer GPUs built with Zig and Vulkan compute shaders. Features continuous batching, paged KV cache, TurboQuant KV compression, and an OpenAI-compatible API.',
      applicationCategory: 'DeveloperApplication',
      operatingSystem: 'Linux',
      url: `${siteUrl}/zinc`,
      codeRepository: 'https://github.com/zolotukhin/zinc',
      author: {
        '@type': 'Person',
        name: 'Stepan Zolotukhin',
        url: `${siteUrl}/about`,
      },
      keywords: 'LLM inference, AMD GPU, RDNA4, RDNA3, Vulkan compute, Zig, TurboQuant, KV cache compression, OpenAI API, local AI, vLLM alternative, llama.cpp alternative',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'FAQPage',
      mainEntity: [
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'Does ZINC work on AMD consumer GPUs like the RX 9070 XT?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'Yes. ZINC is built specifically for AMD RDNA3 and RDNA4 consumer GPUs including the RX 7900 XTX, RX 9070 XT, and Radeon AI PRO R9700. It uses Vulkan compute instead of ROCm, so it works on hardware that vLLM and most CUDA-based tools cannot use.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'How does ZINC compare to llama.cpp and vLLM?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'vLLM requires ROCm which does not support RDNA3/RDNA4 consumer GPUs. llama.cpp supports Vulkan but treats RDNA4 as an afterthought with no architecture-specific tuning, no continuous batching, and no paged KV cache. ZINC is built from scratch for these GPUs with hand-tuned shaders, continuous batching, paged attention, and TurboQuant KV compression.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'What performance does ZINC achieve on RDNA4?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'On the Radeon AI PRO R9700 (32GB, 576 GB/s), ZINC targets 110+ tokens/second on Qwen3.5-35B-A3B Q4_K for single requests, and 108+ tok/s per slot with 4 concurrent requests (432+ tok/s aggregate). DMMV bandwidth utilization is 67-93% of theoretical.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'What is TurboQuant and how does it help?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'TurboQuant is a two-stage vector quantization algorithm (ICLR 2026) that compresses LLM KV cache to 2-4 bits per coordinate. At 3-bit, it achieves 5x memory reduction while preserving 99.5% attention cosine similarity through mathematically unbiased inner products. On a 16GB RX 9070 XT, this means 8+ concurrent 8K-context sessions instead of 4.',
          },
        },
      ],
    },
    buildBreadcrumbList(siteUrl, breadcrumbItems),
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="ZINC — LLM Inference Engine for AMD GPUs"
  description="ZINC is an inference engine for AMD consumer GPUs that ROCm ignores. Built with Zig and Vulkan, with hand-tuned RDNA4 shaders, continuous batching, and TurboQuant KV compression. 110+ tok/s on AI PRO R9700."
  keywords="ZINC, LLM inference engine, AMD GPU, RDNA4, RDNA3, RX 9070 XT, RX 7900 XTX, Radeon AI PRO R9700, Vulkan compute, Zig, TurboQuant, KV cache compression, vLLM alternative, llama.cpp alternative, ROCm alternative, OpenAI compatible API, local AI, continuous batching, paged KV cache, GGUF, LLaMA, Qwen, Mistral, Mamba"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbItems} />
  <section class="hero">
    <img src="/zinc-logo.png" alt="ZINC inference engine logo — lightning bolt on circuit board" class="logo" width="120" height="120" />
    <h1>ZINC — LLM Inference Engine for AMD GPUs</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Fast local LLM inference on AMD consumer GPUs. Not a fallback — a first-class target.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <p>If you have an AMD consumer GPU — an <strong>RX 7900 XTX</strong>, <strong>RX 9070 XT</strong>, or <strong>Radeon AI PRO R9700</strong> — the mainstream AI stack mostly ignores you. <strong>vLLM</strong> requires <a href="https://rocm.docs.amd.com/en/latest/release/gpu_os_support.html">ROCm</a>, which does not support these cards. <strong>llama.cpp</strong> runs via Vulkan but treats RDNA4 as generic hardware with no architecture-specific tuning.</p>

    <p>ZINC takes a different approach. It is an inference engine written in <strong>Zig</strong> with hand-tuned <strong>Vulkan compute shaders</strong>, built specifically for the GPU architecture these cards actually have.</p>

    <h2>Why not vLLM or llama.cpp?</h2>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th></th><th>ZINC</th><th>vLLM</th><th>llama.cpp (Vulkan)</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>RDNA3/RDNA4 support</strong></td><td>First-class target</td><td>Not supported (needs ROCm)</td><td>Works, no RDNA4 tuning</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Continuous batching</strong></td><td>Built-in</td><td>Built-in</td><td>Server-bolted</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Paged KV cache</strong></td><td>vLLM-style PagedAttention</td><td>Yes</td><td>No (contiguous)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>KV cache compression</strong></td><td>TurboQuant 2/3/4-bit</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>GPU kernel tuning</strong></td><td>RDNA4 wave64, coop matrix</td><td>ROCm/CUDA only</td><td>Generic Vulkan</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>OpenAI API</strong></td><td>Native</td><td>Native</td><td>Via server wrapper</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Performance on AMD RDNA4</h2>

    <p>Measured and projected on real RDNA4 hardware. DMMV bandwidth utilization is 67–93% of theoretical. The GPU is the bottleneck, not the software.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>GPU</th><th>VRAM</th><th>Model</th><th>Single-req</th><th>4-concurrent</th><th>Aggregate</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>RX 9070 XT</strong></td><td>16 GB</td><td>Qwen3-8B Q4_K</td><td>130+ tok/s</td><td>120+ each</td><td>480+ tok/s</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>AI PRO R9700</strong></td><td>32 GB</td><td>Qwen3-8B Q4_K</td><td>120+ tok/s</td><td>110+ each</td><td>440+ tok/s</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>AI PRO R9700</strong></td><td>32 GB</td><td>Llama-3.1-70B Q4_K</td><td>35+ tok/s</td><td>32+ each</td><td>128+ tok/s</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Four concurrent requests run with zero per-slot degradation. The GPU stays memory-bandwidth bound at 4x parallelism. In practice, that means a single RX 9070 XT can serve a small team without anyone waiting.</p>

    <h2>What ZINC does</h2>

    <p>The shaders are hand-tuned for RDNA4: <a href="/zinc/docs/rdna4-tuning">wave64, cooperative matrix 16x16x16</a>, architecture-aware tiling. Not generic GPU code that happens to run on AMD.</p>

    <p>Serving uses vLLM-style PagedAttention with continuous batching. 16-token KV cache pages, copy-on-write for shared prefixes, and a scheduler that batches concurrent requests without per-slot degradation.</p>

    <p><a href="/zinc/docs/turboquant-spec">TurboQuant</a> compresses the KV cache to 3 bits per coordinate with 5x memory reduction. It uses Lloyd-Max quantization with QJL residual correction, which keeps the inner product estimator mathematically unbiased. The attention mechanism sees the same distribution as FP16, just with controlled variance. That 5x saving is what lets an RX 9070 XT handle 8 concurrent sessions instead of 4.</p>

    <p>The API is OpenAI-compatible: <code>POST /v1/chat/completions</code> with SSE streaming. Point your existing client at ZINC and it works. <a href="/zinc/docs/api">API reference</a>.</p>

    <p>Models load from GGUF files via direct memory-map to GPU VRAM. Supports Q4_K, Q5_K, Q6_K, Q8_0, and F16 quantization, including split files. Architectures: LLaMA, Mistral, Qwen, MoE, and Mamba/Jamba hybrids.</p>

    <p>The whole thing is written in Zig. No hidden allocations, C ABI direct Vulkan calls, comptime dispatch tables, single binary.</p>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>

    <div class="arch-stack">
      <div class="arch-layer">
        <strong>OpenAI-compatible HTTP API</strong>
        <span>Zig std.http · SSE streaming</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-layer">
        <strong>Request Scheduler</strong>
        <span>Continuous batching · Priority queue · KV management</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-layer">
        <strong>Vulkan Compute Backend</strong>
        <span>RDNA4-tuned shaders (GLSL → SPIR-V) · Cooperative matrix · Fused ops · Flash attention</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-layer">
        <strong>GPU Memory Manager</strong>
        <span>GGUF loader (mmap → DMA) · Paged KV cache · TurboQuant (Q2/Q3/Q4-bit)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-layer arch-hw">
        <strong>AMD RDNA3 / RDNA4</strong>
        <span>RADV / AMDVLK · Vulkan 1.3</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Supported hardware</h2>

    <p>ZINC targets AMD consumer GPUs via Vulkan compute — no ROCm, no CUDA, no proprietary stack required.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>RDNA4</strong>: RX 9070, RX 9070 XT, Radeon AI PRO R9700</li>
      <li><strong>RDNA3</strong>: RX 7900 XTX, RX 7900 XT, RX 7800 XT, RX 7700 XT, RX 7600</li>
      <li><strong>Future</strong>: Intel Arc (same Vulkan path, different tuning), NVIDIA (Vulkan works, not primary target)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Any GPU with Vulkan 1.3 and a working RADV or AMDVLK driver should work. RDNA4 is the primary tuning target.</p>

    <hr />
    <p><a href="/zinc/docs">Documentation</a> · <a href="/zinc/docs/turboquant-spec">TurboQuant spec</a> · <a href="https://github.com/zolotukhin/zinc">GitHub</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .hero {
    text-align: center;
    padding: var(--space-xl) 0;
  }

  .logo {
    border-radius: 12px;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);
  }

  .tagline {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }


  .btn-outline:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .arch-stack {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    overflow: hidden;
    margin: var(--space-lg) 0;
  }

  .arch-layer {
    padding: var(--space-md) var(--space-lg);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.2rem;
  }

  .arch-layer:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .arch-layer strong {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }

  .arch-layer span {
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .arch-hw {
    background: var(--color-bg-alt);
  }
</style>
